      <h1>Ultimate China Travel Guide 2026: Everything You Need to Know</h1>

      <p><strong>Planning a trip to China in 2026?</strong> You're in the right place. This is the guide I wish I had before my first visit — covering visas, routes, budgets, apps, and the stuff nobody tells you until you're standing confused in a Shanghai metro station.</p>

      <p>China has changed fast. Visa-free transit now covers 54 countries, mobile payment works with foreign cards, and high-speed rail connects almost every major city. But the information gap is still huge. Let's fix that.</p>

      <nav aria-label="Table of Contents">
        <h2>📋 In This Guide</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><a href="#visas">Visa & Entry Requirements</a></li>
          <li><a href="#when-to-go">Best Time to Visit China</a></li>
          <li><a href="#routes">Recommended Routes (3–14 Days)</a></li>
          <li><a href="#budget">Budget Breakdown</a></li>
          <li><a href="#internet">Internet, VPN & eSIM</a></li>
          <li><a href="#payments">Payments: WeChat, Alipay & Cash</a></li>
          <li><a href="#transport">Getting Around: Trains, Flights & Metro</a></li>
          <li><a href="#accommodation">Where to Stay</a></li>
          <li><a href="#food">What to Eat (Without Getting Sick)</a></li>
          <li><a href="#faq">FAQ</a></li>
        </ol>
      </nav>

      <h2 id="visas">🛂 Visa & Entry Requirements</h2>

      <h3>Visa-Free Transit (144-Hour / 6-Day)</h3>
      <p>Citizens from <strong>54 countries</strong> — including the US, UK, EU, Australia, Canada, and Japan — can enter China visa-free for up to 144 hours (6 days) when transiting to a third country. This covers most major cities: Beijing, Shanghai, Guangzhou, Chengdu, Xi'an, Chongqing, and more.</p>

      <p><strong>The catch:</strong> You must arrive from Country A, enter China, then depart to Country B (not back to A). Example: London → Beijing → Tokyo works. London → Beijing → London does not.</p>

      <h3>Tourist Visa (L Visa)</h3>
      <p>If you're staying longer than 6 days or visiting multiple cities beyond the transit zones, get a tourist visa. Standard processing takes 4–5 business days. Cost varies by nationality ($140 for US citizens). You'll need:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Valid passport (6+ months validity, 2+ blank pages)</li>
        <li>Completed visa application form</li>
        <li>Round-trip flight itinerary + hotel bookings</li>
        <li>Passport photo (33mm × 48mm, white background)</li>
      </ul>

      <p><strong>2026 update:</strong> Several countries (France, Germany, Italy, Netherlands, Spain, Malaysia) now have 15-day visa-free entry for tourism. Check the latest policy before you apply — the list keeps growing.</p>

      <h2 id="when-to-go">🌤️ Best Time to Visit China</h2>

      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Season</th><th>Months</th><th>Best For</th><th>Crowds</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Spring</td><td>Mar–May</td><td>🌸 Mild weather, flowers blooming</td><td>Moderate</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Autumn</td><td>Sep–Nov</td><td>🍂 Perfect temps, clear skies, golden foliage</td><td>High (Oct holiday)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Summer</td><td>Jun–Aug</td><td>🏔️ Mountains, Tibet, Inner Mongolia</td><td>High (school break)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Winter</td><td>Dec–Feb</td><td>❄️ Harbin Ice Festival, cheaper flights, ski</td><td>Low (except CNY)</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <p><strong>My pick: mid-September to late October.</strong> The weather is perfect across most of China, and the autumn colors in places like Huangshan and Jiuzhaigou are unreal. Avoid the first week of October (Golden Week) — every tourist site becomes a sea of humanity.</p>

      <h2 id="routes">🗺️ Recommended Routes</h2>

      <h3>3 Days: The Golden Triangle</h3>
      <p>If you only have 3 days, do Beijing and Shanghai. Fly into Beijing, take the high-speed train to Shanghai (4.5 hours), fly out from Shanghai. <a href="/guides/beijing/beijing-3-day-golden-triangle">See our full Beijing 3-day guide →</a></p>

      <h3>7 Days: Classic First-Timer</h3>
      <p>Beijing (3 days) → Xi'an (2 days) → Shanghai (2 days). This hits the "big three" — Great Wall, Forbidden City, Terracotta Warriors, and the Bund. All connected by high-speed rail. <a href="/guides/beijing/beijing-xian-shanghai-7-day-golden-triangle">Full 7-day itinerary →</a></p>

      <h3>10 Days: Culture + Nature</h3>
      <p>Beijing (3 days) → Xi'an (2 days) → Chengdu (2 days, pandas!) → Guilin/Yangshuo (3 days, karst landscapes). The diversity on this route is incredible. <a href="/guides/chengdu/chengdu-panda-nature-3-day">Chengdu panda guide →</a> | <a href="/guides/guilin/guilin-yangshuo-river-karst-3-day">Guilin karst guide →</a></p>

      <h3>14 Days: The Full Experience</h3>
      <p>Shanghai (2 days) → Beijing (3 days) → Xi'an (2 days) → Chengdu (2 days) → Chongqing (2 days) → Yangtze River cruise (3 days). This is the ambitious route. It works, but you'll need solid planning. <a href="/guides/shanghai/shanghai-3-day-casual">Start with Shanghai →</a></p>

      <h2 id="budget">💰 Budget Breakdown</h2>

      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Category</th><th>Budget ($)</th><th>Mid-Range ($)</th><th>Luxury ($)</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Accommodation (per night)</td><td>$15–30</td><td>$50–100</td><td>$150+</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Meals (per day)</td><td>$10–15</td><td>$25–40</td><td>$60+</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Transport (intercity, per trip)</td><td>$20–40 (train)</td><td>$60–120 (HSR)</td><td>$100–300 (flight)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Attractions (per site)</td><td>$5–10</td><td>$15–30</td><td>$50+</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Daily Total</strong></td><td><strong>$35–55</strong></td><td><strong>$80–150</strong></td><td><strong>$200–400</strong></td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <p><strong>A comfortable 10-day trip runs about $800–1,500 per person</strong> (mid-range). You can do it for $500 on a shoestring, or go wild at $4,000+. The single biggest variable is hotels — Chinese domestic hotel chains are excellent and cheap ($30–60/night for a clean private room).</p>

      <h2 id="internet">📶 Internet, VPN & eSIM in China</h2>

      <p>The Great Firewall is real. Google, Instagram, WhatsApp, Facebook, YouTube, Twitter/X — all blocked. You need a VPN <strong>before</strong> you land. Airport WiFi requires a Chinese phone number to log in, so you can't download a VPN after arrival.</p>

      <p>We have a detailed guide covering every option: <a href="/guides/general/internet-vpn">China VPN & eSIM Guide →</a></p>

      <p><strong>Quick summary:</strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>eSIM (easiest):</strong> Airalo or Saily. Install before departure, activate on landing. Bypasses the firewall for data, but doesn't give you a Chinese phone number. <a href="https://airalo.tp.st/4w5I5IQK" rel="nofollow sponsored">Get Airalo →</a></li>
        <li><strong>VPN (most flexible):</strong> Install a reliable VPN before you leave. We've tested several — <a href="https://365vpn.net" rel="nofollow sponsored">365VPN</a> and <a href="https://protonvpn.com" rel="nofollow">ProtonVPN</a> consistently work inside China.</li>
        <li><strong>Local SIM:</strong> China Unicom tourist SIM at the airport ($30 for 7 days). Gives you a local number (needed for some apps), but still needs a VPN for Google services.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 id="payments">💳 Payments: WeChat, Alipay & Cash</h2>

      <p>China is nearly cashless. Even street vendors take QR code payments. Here's what you need to know as a foreigner:</p>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>Alipay (best for foreigners):</strong> You can now link international credit cards (Visa, Mastercard) directly. Download the app, verify your passport, link your card. Works everywhere. <a href="/guides/general/first-time-china-survival#payments">Step-by-step setup guide →</a></li>
        <li><strong>WeChat Pay:</strong> Also accepts foreign cards now, but the verification process is more finicky than Alipay.</li>
        <li><strong>Cash:</strong> Still accepted, but many small vendors won't have change. Carry some as backup (¥500–1000 is plenty).</li>
      </ul>

      <p><strong>Pro tip:</strong> Set up Alipay at least 3 days before your trip. The passport verification takes time, and you don't want to be stuck at a restaurant unable to pay.</p>

      <h2 id="transport">🚄 Getting Around</h2>

      <h3>High-Speed Rail</h3>
      <p>China's high-speed rail network is the world's largest and it's genuinely impressive. Beijing to Shanghai (1,318 km) in 4.5 hours. Clean, punctual, and cheap by Western standards. Book tickets via <a href="https://www.trip.com" rel="nofollow">Trip.com</a> (English interface, accepts foreign cards).</p>

      <h3>Domestic Flights</h3>
      <p>For distances over 1,000 km, flying is often cheaper than high-speed rail. China Eastern, Air China, and China Southern are the big three. Book 2–4 weeks ahead for best prices.</p>

      <h3>City Metro</h3>
      <p>Every major city has a modern metro system. Fares are $0.50–1.50 per ride. All signage is bilingual (Chinese + English). Alipay's "Transport" mini-app handles metro/bus payments in most cities.</p>

      <h3>Didi (China's Uber)</h3>
      <p>Available in English via the Didi app or directly inside Alipay. Cheap (a 30-minute ride costs $5–10). The built-in translation feature lets you message drivers in English.</p>

      <h2 id="accommodation">🏨 Where to Stay</h2>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>Trip.com (formerly Ctrip):</strong> Best for booking hotels in China. English interface, foreign cards, reliable. Often cheaper than Booking.com for Chinese properties.</li>
        <li><strong>Booking.com / Agoda:</strong> Work fine but have fewer listings and sometimes higher prices for domestic hotels.</li>
        <li><strong>Hostels:</strong> Excellent in China — clean, social, and $10–20/night. Many cater specifically to foreign travelers.</li>
      </ul>

      <p><strong>Registration note:</strong> Hotels automatically register you with the local police (required by law). If you're staying at an Airbnb or friend's place, you may need to register at the local police station yourself within 24 hours. Your host should help with this.</p>

      <h2 id="food">🍜 What to Eat (Without Getting Sick)</h2>

      <p>Chinese food in China is not Chinese food in the West. It's better. Much better. But a few rules will keep your stomach happy:</p>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>Eat where locals eat.</strong> A busy restaurant at 12:30 PM is busy for a reason. High turnover = fresh ingredients.</li>
        <li><strong>Drink bottled or boiled water.</strong> Tap water is not safe to drink anywhere in China. Hotels provide kettles.</li>
        <li><strong>Street food is generally safe</strong> if it's cooked hot in front of you. Avoid raw/cold street food on day one.</li>
        <li><strong>Learn three phrases:</strong> "bù là" (not spicy), "xiè xiè" (thank you), "mǎi dān" (check please). A little Chinese goes a long way.</li>
        <li><strong>Use translation apps for menus.</strong> Google Translate's camera mode works (if your VPN is on). Point your camera at a menu, read in English.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 id="faq">❓ Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <h3>Do I need to speak Chinese?</h3>
      <p>No, but it helps. In major cities (Beijing, Shanghai, Guangzhou), you can get by with English + translation apps. In smaller cities, prepare to use hand gestures and Google Translate. Chinese people are generally very helpful to foreign tourists, even with the language barrier.</p>

      <h3>Is China safe for tourists?</h3>
      <p>Extremely safe. Violent crime against foreigners is almost nonexistent. The biggest risks are scams (tea ceremony scam, "art student" scam) and traffic (look both ways, drivers don't always stop for pedestrians). Use common sense and you'll be fine.</p>

      <h3>Can I use Google Maps in China?</h3>
      <p>Google Maps works with a VPN, but it's not accurate for China. Use <strong>Apple Maps</strong> (works without VPN, surprisingly) or <strong>Baidu Maps</strong> (Chinese only, but most accurate). <strong>Maps.me</strong> and <strong>Organic Maps</strong> are good offline alternatives for hiking and rural areas.</p>

      <h3>What about the internet firewall?</h3>
      <p>Yes, China blocks Google, Facebook, Instagram, WhatsApp, YouTube, Twitter, and many news sites. Install a VPN <strong>before arriving</strong> and you'll be fine. We've tested multiple VPNs inside China — <a href="/guides/general/internet-vpn">see our VPN guide for recommendations →</a></p>

      <h3>How much does 10 days in China cost?</h3>
      <p>Budget: $500. Mid-range: $800–1,500. Luxury: $3,000+. Flights to/from China are usually the biggest expense. Internal costs (food, transport, hotels) are surprisingly affordable. <a href="#budget">See our full budget breakdown above →</a></p>

      <hr />

      <p><strong>Ready to plan your trip?</strong> Browse our <a href="/guides/">full collection of city guides</a>, each written by travelers who've been there. Or start with our <a href="/guides/general/first-time-china-survival">First Time in China survival guide →</a></p>
